Problems

1. False-positive health report  
   • The code returns `{"status":"ok"}` even when the database check fails (`catch(() => …)`).  
   • A load-balancer, orchestrator (K8s, ECS, etc.) or monitoring tool will keep routing traffic to an instance that cannot talk to its database.

2. Wrong / missing HTTP status codes  
   • A successful readiness check should be HTTP 200.  
   • A failed readiness check should be 5xx (usually 503 = Service Unavailable).  
   • At the moment everything is returned with the default 200 status.

3. Silent error handling  
   • The error is swallowed—nothing is logged and `next(err)` is not called.  
   • Makes debugging difficult and hides operational problems.

4. Possible connection-pool leakage / unnecessary query  
   • If `db.query` opens a dedicated connection and the promise is rejected before the connection is returned to the pool, you may leak connections.  
   • `SELECT 1` is fine, but most drivers offer a cheaper “ping” or `pool.query('SELECT 1')` that re-uses pooled connections.

5. No timeout / circuit-breaker  
   • If the database is down, the call can block for tens of seconds, tying up an event-loop thread and making the whole process look healthy to the LB while it is actually stuck.

6. Missing `return` in the promise chain (minor)  
   • The handler does not have to return the promise, but doing so makes testing easier and means Express will not treat unhandled rejections as uncaught errors.

7. Potential information disclosure (optional)  
   • Although the code currently hides the exact error, in many teams the temptation is to change the health route later to return `err.message`, leaking internal details.

Recommended fix

```javascript
// health.js
const express = require('express');
const router = express.Router();

/**
 * Readiness probe.
 * Returns 200 if DB reachable, 503 otherwise.
 * Adds a 2 s timeout and proper error logging.
 */
router.get('/health', async (req, res, next) => {
  try {
    // race the DB query against a timeout so we don’t block forever
    await Promise.race([
      db.query('SELECT 1'),
      new Promise((_, reject) => setTimeout(
        () => reject(new Error('DB health-check timed out')), 2000
      ))
    ]);

    return res.status(200).json({ status: 'ok' });      // ready
  } catch (err) {
    // log for observability (replace console with your logger)
    console.error('[health-check] database error:', err);

    // Let monitoring/LB know we’re NOT ready
    return res.status(503).json({ status: 'error' });
  }
});

module.exports = router;
```

Additional hardening / improvements

• If you separate “liveness” (process up) from “readiness” (dependencies up), expose two endpoints: `/live` that just returns 200, `/ready` that runs the DB check.  
• Put the check behind a minimal auth mechanism or IP allow-list if it must not be publicly exposed.  
• Hook the errors into a global error handler (`next(err)`) if you have one.  
• Consider a circuit-breaker library (`opossum`, `cockatiel`, etc.) to prevent hammering an unhealthy DB.  
• Cache the positive result for a few hundred milliseconds to handle traffic spikes from aggressive health checkers.

The changes above make the route truthful, observable, and production-ready.
